proofread NEWS -- history of user-visible changes.

This file records notable user-visible changes to proofread and
proofread-popup.  For detailed development history, see the Git log.


* Changes in proofread 0.3.0

** Incompatible changes

---
*** The legacy single-backend configuration has been removed.
Proofread no longer reads the obsolete 'proofread-backend' and
'proofread-language' variables.  Setting either variable has no effect on
backend dispatch.  A nil 'proofread-profile' now disables backend dispatch, as
does a named profile with an empty ':checkers' list.

To migrate, define a named entry in 'proofread-profiles', move the language to
the profile's ':language' property, represent each backend with a named checker
whose ':backend' property selects it, and select the profile with
'proofread-profile'.

** User interface

---
*** Request and diagnostic lists now report display columns.
The 'Col' field uses Emacs's zero-based display column, so tabs, wide
characters, and combining characters are represented as they appear on screen.


* Changes in proofread 0.2.0

** Configuration

---
*** Profiles and checkers are now the primary configuration interface.
The user option 'proofread-profile' selects a named entry from
'proofread-profiles'.  Each profile can specify ':language',
':display-language', and an ordered ':checkers' list.  Each checker has a unique
symbol ':name', selects a registered backend with ':backend', and can carry
backend-specific ':options'.  Multiple checkers can therefore proofread the same
text with different backends or settings.

The profile ':language' is a machine-readable language code, while
':display-language' is the human-readable language name used in LLM prompts.
LLM requests prefer ':display-language', fall back to ':language', and omit the
target-language hint when both are nil.  LanguageTool continues to use the
checker-local ':language' when that key is present (including nil for automatic
detection), falls back to the profile ':language' when the key is absent, and
never receives the display name.

An empty ':checkers' list disables proofreading for that profile.
'proofread-profile' can also be set buffer-locally to select different profiles
in different buffers.

---
*** The legacy single-backend configuration is now obsolete.
The user options 'proofread-backend' and 'proofread-language' are both obsolete
as of proofread 0.2.0.  They remain functional for compatibility in this
release.  An actual check that uses the legacy configuration issues one warning
per Emacs session.

To migrate, define a named entry in 'proofread-profiles', move the old language
value to the profile's ':language' property, represent the old backend with a
named checker whose ':backend' property selects it, and select the profile with
'proofread-profile'.

** Backends

---
*** Proofread mode now aligns LLM connection and request timeouts.
When 'proofread-mode' is enabled, the current 'proofread-llm-request-timeout' is
used as the buffer-local 'llm-request-plz-connect-timeout'.  Disabling the mode
or unloading the LLM backend restores the previous local binding or current
global value.

---
*** New local LanguageTool backend.
The new backend sends asynchronous HTTP requests to a LanguageTool v2 server.
It supports safe UTF-16 offset conversion, configurable language and rule
selection, request timeouts, and optional management of a session-local
LanguageTool server.

LanguageTool remains an optional runtime dependency used only by LanguageTool
checkers.

---
*** New backend registry.
The core now dispatches through a backend registry.  The registry supports lazy
loading, backend-specific cache identities, and backend-specific request
cancellation.

---
*** Checker dispatch failures are isolated within a profile.
Failures while loading a backend, computing checker identity, constructing
requests, or submitting them are reported for that checker.  Remaining checkers
in the profile continue to run.

---
*** Unloading the LLM backend safely terminates active requests.
Unloading "proofread-llm" now cancels live provider work and timers and settles
the related core requests exactly once.  Late provider callbacks are ignored,
preventing void-function errors and occupied scheduler slots during unload or
reload.

---
*** Fallback LLM provider identities no longer collide after reload.
Automatically generated identities now differ across loads of "proofread-llm",
so a different provider with the same name cannot reuse stale cache entries.
Explicit ':provider-identity' values remain stable for intentional cache reuse.

---
*** LLM requests now have a Proofread-owned timeout watchdog.
The new option 'proofread-llm-request-timeout' defaults to 120 seconds; nil
disables it.  A checker-local ':request-timeout' takes precedence whenever the
key is present, including nil.  A timeout cancels provider work and releases the
core scheduler slot.  Timeout settings affect liveness, not cache compatibility.

---
*** LanguageTool distinguishes HTTP responses from transport failures.
Non-200 responses with a valid HTTP status now report a
'languagetool-http-error' and retain the status and bounded response body in the
error details.  Such responses keep a reachable server ready.
'languagetool-transport-error' is reserved for failures without a valid HTTP
response; malformed successful responses remain invalid-response errors.

---
*** Managed LanguageTool identities now track configuration contents.
For servers owned by Proofread, the normalized configuration content digest and
resolved command identity now participate in startup and cache identity.
Changing the configuration or replacing the executable at the same path restarts
a ready owned server and prevents reuse of old cached results.  Configuration
contents are not exposed in logs, and external servers are not restarted.

** User interface

---
*** Diagnostics now carry frontend source labels.
Backends can provide one safe display label per checker without changing the raw
backend source stored in diagnostics and used by ignoring.  LLM checkers use an
explicit ':source-label', the new 'proofread-llm-source-label' default, or the
effective provider name; LanguageTool uses "languagetool".  The new public
diagnostic message-entry interface preserves each message-to-source association
for frontends, including aggregate diagnostics and cache hits.

---
*** Diagnostics at point now appear in the echo area.
When 'proofread-echo-area-messages' is non-nil, 'proofread-mode' registers an
ElDoc provider that displays the diagnostic at point as "Source: message".
Messages from multiple checkers retain profile order and share one line.  The
new option defaults to non-nil and becomes buffer-local when set.

The new 'proofread-echo-area-source-face' inherits
'font-lock-keyword-face', while 'proofread-echo-area-message-face' inherits
'font-lock-comment-face'.  The public 'proofread-format-diagnostic-message'
function lets optional frontends reuse the same source-aware fallback and
aggregation rules with independent faces and separators.  proofread-popup now
uses this shared formatter.

---
*** Explicit checks now retire diagnostics owned by inactive checkers.
After a profile switch or checker removal, explicitly checking a range removes
diagnostics in that range that belong to checkers absent from the current
profile, even if no replacement diagnostics are reported.  An empty profile
similarly retires profile-owned diagnostics from the checked range without
dispatching backend requests.  Diagnostics outside the checked range remain
unchanged.  Profile-owner retirement does not affect otherwise-valid ad-hoc
low-level diagnostics, while diagnostics from current checkers remain visible
until their replacement results are applied.

---
*** Matching diagnostics from multiple checkers are aggregated.
Diagnostics for the same text and range remain independent internally but are
presented as one source-aware diagnostic for navigation, descriptions,
suggestions, correction, and ignoring.  Grouped sources, messages, suggestions,
and correction choices follow the profile's declared checker order, regardless
of asynchronous completion order.

---
*** Request monitoring excludes configuration secrets and opaque objects.
All request-log events, stored records, and detail buffers now use a safe
representation that omits raw checker options, provider objects, backend
handles, and other opaque backend-local objects.

Logged URLs retain only their origin (scheme, host, and port).  Backend errors
and related warnings retain only the condition kind rather than raw payloads or
messages.  Checker fingerprints are derived from safe identity summaries, not
raw options.

Source text, generated prompt text, HTTP request parameters, and provider
responses remain visible for debugging and may contain sensitive text.

** Performance

---
*** Diagnostic lookup at point now examines only local diagnostics.
Looking up a diagnostic for commands or optional frontends no longer traverses
and sorts every diagnostic in the buffer.  Matching diagnostics at point retain
the same source-aware aggregation and ordering.

---
*** Large asynchronous checks remain responsive with caching enabled.
Successful backend replies now wake only queued requests that can use the new
cache entry.  This avoids repeated scans of unrelated queued work in buffers
split into many chunks, without changing cache-hit behavior, checker isolation,
or request ordering.

** Packaging and development

---
*** Package sources have been reorganized.
The proofread package sources now live under "lisp/proofread/".  The
implementation is split into "proofread.el", "proofread-llm.el", and
"proofread-languagetool.el".

---
*** Backend-private implementation details use feature namespaces.
Backend-private functions and variables now live under their feature namespaces.
Shared callback scheduling and position conversion are centralized in the core
library.

---
*** Tests are split by backend.
Core, LLM, and LanguageTool tests are now independent suites.  Backend test
symbols are aligned with their feature namespaces.

---
*** The core library no longer loads GNU ELPA llm eagerly.
The core library does not load GNU ELPA "llm" until the LLM backend is selected
or required explicitly.

** Compatibility

---
*** proofread 0.2.0 remains compatible with proofread-popup 0.1.0.
The core retains the compatibility entry points used by the released popup.
Users may therefore upgrade proofread before upgrading the optional popup
frontend.


* Changes in proofread 0.1.0

Initial release.

** Proofreading

---
*** Asynchronous, context-aware proofreading.
Proofread provides asynchronous, context-aware proofreading through provider
objects from the GNU ELPA "llm" package.

---
*** LLM JSON response handling.
Proofread supports provider-enforced JSON schema responses and prompt-only JSON
responses, with automatic selection based on provider capabilities.

---
*** Automatic and explicit checks.
Proofread can check visible text automatically after idle time.  It also
provides explicit commands for checking the text at point, the active region,
the accessible buffer, or all visible ranges.

---
*** Mode-aware text selection.
Proofread can select ordinary text, comments, or docstrings with mode-aware
defaults.  It excludes URLs, email addresses, invisible text, configured faces,
and configured text properties.

---
*** Sentence-aware request chunking.
Proofread splits prose into bounded, sentence-aware requests with configurable
surrounding context.

---
*** Overlay diagnostics and navigation.
Diagnostics are displayed with overlays.  Commands are provided for navigation,
detailed descriptions, and a tabulated buffer-wide diagnostic list.

---
*** Interactive and batch correction.
Proofread can correct individual diagnostics or scoped groups of diagnostics.
Batch corrections are applied atomically as one undo step and roll back on
failure.

---
*** Session-local ignore records.
Proofread can ignore semantically identical diagnostics for the current Emacs
session.

---
*** Caching, concurrency, and stale-result handling.
Proofread caches diagnostics per buffer, queues requests behind a configurable
concurrency limit, rejects stale results after edits, and preserves usable
results when only part of a check fails.

---
*** Request lifecycle recording.
Proofread can record and inspect complete request lifecycles on demand,
including queued, active, completed, failed, and stale requests.


* Changes in proofread-popup 0.1.1

** Popup display

---
*** Child-frame updates wait for point to become idle.
Popup updates now coalesce movement and diagnostic notifications, then recompute
the display from the final state after point has been idle.  The new
'proofread-popup-delay' option defaults to 0.5 seconds; set it to zero to
restore immediate updates.

---
*** Popups no longer linger after their source display loses selection.
A child frame is now hidden immediately when its source buffer or window loses
selection, including switches and programmatic window changes.

---
*** Popup messages identify their backend source.
Every diagnostic message is displayed on its own line with its LLM or
LanguageTool source label.  Source labels use the new
'proofread-popup-source-face', which inherits 'font-lock-keyword-face'.  Message
text inherits 'font-lock-comment-face' through 'proofread-popup-face'.

---
*** Equal aggregate diagnostics no longer cause redundant redraws.
Repeated updates for an unchanged aggregate diagnostic now reuse the existing
popup.  Changes to the displayed message, anchor, selected window, or render
state still refresh it.

** Compatibility

---
*** proofread-popup now requires proofread 0.2.0.
This release uses the public frontend integration interfaces introduced in
proofread 0.2.0.  Update the core package before installing this version of
proofread-popup.

** Packaging

---
*** The source file now lives in its package directory.
Source-checkout installations should add "lisp/proofread-popup" to 'load-path'.


* Changes in proofread-popup 0.1.0

Initial release.

** Popup display

---
*** Optional Posframe frontend.
The proofread-popup package provides an optional Posframe frontend that displays
the diagnostic at point in a child frame.

---
*** Automatic integration with proofread-mode.
proofread-popup follows 'proofread-mode' automatically while allowing popup
display to be disabled per buffer.

---
*** Customizable popup appearance.
Popup width, text appearance, and border appearance are customizable.


